⸻

Context

Every event is interpreted within context.

Context includes:

* company
* user
* date
* accounting period
* fiscal calendar
* historical behaviour
* current workflow
* previous interactions

Context changes interpretation.

The same invoice may produce different actions depending on context.

⸻

Business Events

Numera represents the company as a continuous sequence of business events.

Examples:

Invoice received.

Payment executed.

Supplier created.

Price increased.

Tax filed.

Contract signed.

User correction accepted.

Every event becomes knowledge.

⸻

Company Memory

Company memory is independent from documents.

Examples:

Supplier always invoices on Fridays.

This supplier often sends duplicates.

Manager prefers manual approval above €5,000.

Fuel invoices use account 629300.

These are memories.

Not invoices.

⸻

Dynamic Knowledge

Knowledge evolves.

The graph must allow:

* adding new relationships;
* removing obsolete relationships;
* strengthening trusted relationships;
* weakening outdated knowledge.

Knowledge is dynamic.

⸻

Time

Everything in Numera exists in time.

Every entity should know:

* when it was created;
* when it changed;
* when it became obsolete;
* what replaced it.

Time is fundamental for reasoning.

⸻

Trust

Every relationship carries confidence.

Example:

Supplier → Account 628

Confidence: 99%

Supplier → Account 629

Confidence: 41%

Relationships are probabilistic.

Not absolute.

⸻

Knowledge Ownership

Every company owns its graph.

Graphs must remain isolated.

No company may access another company’s knowledge.

Learning is company-specific unless explicitly designed otherwise.

⸻

Closing Statement

Numera does not understand companies through spreadsheets or accounting tables.

Numera understands companies through relationships.

Every document is an event.

Every event creates knowledge.

Every piece of knowledge changes future decisions.

The Enterprise Knowledge Model defines the conceptual world in which the Numera Brain operates.